            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> my terminal supports 256 colors, and I damn well want to see them!\r\n\r\nI know most terminal environments support 256 colors, but it's still not all. Even though I use a terminal with truecolor support, I still often find I'm in situtations where the shell isn't properly set up. Therefore I still think it's important that the `nvim -u NONE` works as best it can in as many environements as possible and I don't think using 16 colors degrades the experience much since the colorscheme is only 20 colors. If it required a larger set of the 255 space then that would tip the argument.\r\n\r\n> Since we can't meet both, we need to be ready to compromise, or have good objective arguments why the project favors one over the other.\r\n\r\nI would have thought the option that is adaptive and synergizes with other systems is much more of the Nvim ethos as opposed to: \"you will use these colors!\". Honestly, the fact that the scheme is mostly blue/green is opionative enough. Further forcing the palette is just going too far for the default scheme.\r\n\r\nFrom my perspective, the whole 256 color thing never properly took off and is now superseded by truecolor. Whereas 16 color is still very much prevalent and is what most CLI applications stick too.\r\n\r\nI think the compromise is that the `termguicolors` variant is the authoritive \"this is our colorscheme!\". Whereas I strongly think the `notermguicolors` variant needs to back off a bit and only focus on part 2). of the colorscheme.",
