            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> Therefore we should be able to rework the colorscheme to only use the `cterm0-15` colors and provide a terminal configuration for users who wish use the new Nvim palette. Since the palette requires 4 additional colors either:\r\n> \r\n>     * pull these from the 17-255 space.\r\n> \r\n>     * merge these shades of grey into white, black, \"dark white\" and \"bright black\".\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, non of these approaches are fully possible. For text foreground (red, green, yellow, blue, magenta, cyan) - yes, it is a matter of straightforward replacement, as those correspond to terminal colors (with intent of compatibility, as it is).\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to text background it is a bit less straightforward, as it needs to be different from what is used in the foreground (or it will lead to no text at all). So such highlight groups should only have non-colored foreground. I think it is already the case in default, but not entirely sure.\r\n\r\nThe most problematic is indeed 4 additional grey colors. They define how UI looks. Pulling these from 16-255 space will not lead to entirely usable palette, as those can equal to some of user's 0-15.\r\n\r\nMerging shades into 0, 7, 8, 15 will also result into not really usable palette as there needs to be shade distinctions in the following levels: NormalFloat - Normal (bg) - CursorLine and Pmenu - Visual - Comment - StatusLineNC - Normal (fg). Those are not really possible to merge into 4 shades and still have a usable UI (I tried). The only route I could find is to go Vim's one: underlined `CursorLine`, reverse `Visual`, magenta `Pmenu` and `NormalFloat`. I would advise against that.\r\n\r\n------\r\n\r\nI know the next question might sound a bit snarky, but I assure you it is not. Why the 16 colors? Why not 8 colors, as I am sure there are only 8 colors terminals out there.\r\n\r\n------\r\n\r\n > Keep in mind 256 colors is the default experience for new users and `nvim --clean`.\r\n\r\nThat is one of the main reasons why I consider having *good* visual UI for `tgc` is important. And I personally could not find one with less than 4 shades of dark and 4 shades of light greys.",
