        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> When it comes to text background it is a bit less straightforward, as it needs to be different from what is used in the foreground (or it will lead to no text at all). So such highlight groups should only have non-colored foreground. I think it is already the case in default, but not entirely sure.\n\nThe background usually always matches or is close to color 0, or, is distinct from all other colors in the 0-15 space. I don't think this was really an issue with the default scheme?\n\n> I know the next question might sound a bit snarky, but I assure you it is not. Why the 16 colors? Why not 8 colors, as I am sure there are only 8 colors terminals out there.\n\nWe could go 8, however I think 16 covers 99.9% of use cases and is much easier to achieve a compromised solution. Though if we can make 8 work then that would be ok with me.\n\n> But we don't need to fully support 16-color, as long as it \"readable\".\n\nI don't think it will be readable if we only use the 17-255 space.\n\n> People who care about full 16-color fidelity can use :colors vim.\n\nThis is exactly why I highlighted the two components of a colorscheme as `:colors vim` handles 2). (the actual scheme) horribly. The new scheme (igoring the palette) is a big improvement.\n\n> 'termguicolors' forces RGB, terminfo is ignored:\n\nThis might have changed but from my experience some emulators use different escape codes. I remember having problems with tmux which uses a different set of escape codes.",
