            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> Sensing a no-win situation. The way we deal with this kind of \"terminal-tradition hell\" is to declare bankruptcy and focus on the common case.\r\n> \r\n>     * If there are some small low-risk tweaks we can make to improve the 16-color situation, fine.\r\n> \r\n>     * But we don't need to fully support 16-color, as long as it \"readable\".\r\n> \r\n>     * People who care about full 16-color fidelity can use `:colors vim`.\r\n\r\nThe best approach I can think of is to replace red, green, and cyan in `ctermfg` with 1, 2, and 6. But having this small of a change doesn't look as being worth it.\r\n\r\n------\r\n\r\n> The background usually always matches or is close to color 0, or, is distinct from all other colors in the 0-15 space. I don't think this was really an issue with the default scheme?\r\n\r\nI meant colored background, like `Diff*`, `Search`, etc.\r\n\r\n------\r\n\r\n> We could go 8, however I think 16 covers 99.9% of use cases and is much easier to achieve a compromised solution. Though if we can make 8 work then that would be ok with me.\r\n\r\nAnd with 256 colors it is about at least 95% of actual user base (i.e. terminals weighted by their usage)? Not sure where to find the actual numbers. [Here](https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Features/256_Color_Terminals#Terminal_256_color_support_list) is one list, but it is far from being full in \"Supports 256 colors\" and a bit outdated or misleading in \"Doesn't support 256 colors\"",
