        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> And with 256 colors it is about at least 95% of actual user base (i.e. terminals weighted by their usage)? Not sure where to find the actual numbers. Here is one list, but it is far from being full in \"Supports 256 colors\" and a bit outdated or misleading in \"Doesn't support 256 colors\"\n\n~I definitely wouldn't go by that measure. In most enterprise environments it's common for xterm to be the only available terminal which only got true color in 2017 which is recent by enterprise standards.~  EDIT: yeah 256 colors is very well supported, but that doesn't really go against my arguments.\n\nThe crux of the issue is that I want the scheme to use my configured colors, not some hardcoded set I can't change without having nvim configured.",
